			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Seems to me that the entire theme of the post is:  Abortion as a method of birth control. Not only as a choice of the mother but by government as well.
<br />

<br />
My personal stance on abortion as the choice of the mother is that it is the mothers moral and personal responsibility.  Society has no say in the matter at all.  The father should have no say as well.  He was able to prevent conception and a man must realize his birthright as a male is one doomed to never bear children. (Here! I-- I've got an idea. Suppose you agree that he can't actually have babies, not having a womb, which is nobody's fault, not even the Romans', but that he can have the right to have babies.)
<br />

<br />
Nature put the responsibility of the fetus on the mother and thats exactly where it belongs as a matter of law.  If a woman wants assurance of support from the father, it is her duty to secure a contract before conception.
<br />

<br />
As far as government goes, to my way of thinking, government does not exist to engineer its society.  The society should be engineering the government.  To start screening genes, is the making of a terrible travesty.  It is ethnic cleansing at a deeper and more dangerous level.  It is not the right of one man to end the genetic vector of another man in the gene pool.
<br />

<br />
Even passive manipulation by government is repugnant to me.  To give the government ANY control over reproduction is a cancerous root in the balance of government serving the people it governs or it dictating those same to serve itself.
<br />

<br />
It is not a matter of what tri-mester the government should put its stamp of approval on.  It should instead be, people removing the dominion of reproduction from government oversight completely.  It is a health issue and like all things it is the mothers natural responsibility to make the best decisions and only submit to medical procedures with informed consent.
<br />

<br />
The idea that a government would seek to limit anyone from reproducing, whether by force or by mandated economic pressure, impacts me at such a basic level that fight or flight instinct immeditately kicks in.  I am a westerner however, and much of what I have observed in eastern thought leads me to believe they think quite differently about the value of an individual.
<br />

<br />
EDIT - Monty Python correction before someone else posts shame for getting it wrong.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
